1
00:00:01,069 --> 00:00:06,270
Developed by Larry Williams, the ultimate
oscillator is a momentum indicator designed

2
00:00:06,270 --> 00:00:09,690
to capture momentum across three different
timeframes.

3
00:00:09,690 --> 00:00:15,280
The multiple timeframe objective seeks to
avoid the pitfalls of other oscillators.

4
00:00:15,280 --> 00:00:20,490
Many momentum oscillators surge at the beginning
of a strong advance, only to form a bearish

5
00:00:20,490 --> 00:00:23,240
divergence as the advance continues.

6
00:00:23,240 --> 00:00:26,259
This is because they are stuck with one timeframe.

7
00:00:26,259 --> 00:00:31,699
The ultimate oscillator attempts to correct
this fault by incorporating longer timeframes

8
00:00:31,699 --> 00:00:33,570
into the basic formula.

9
00:00:33,570 --> 00:00:39,090
The ultimate oscillator combines short-term,
intermediate-term, and long-term price action

10
00:00:39,090 --> 00:00:45,370
into one oscillator and attempts to give overbought
and oversold signals, potential buy and sell

11
00:00:45,370 --> 00:00:51,340
readings, and confirmations of price action
as well as divergences that might warn of

12
00:00:51,340 --> 00:00:54,519
future price reversals.

13
00:00:54,519 --> 00:00:59,050
The default settings of the ultimate oscillator
is 7,14,28.

14
00:00:59,050 --> 00:01:05,330
First, the oscillator calculates buying pressure
to determine the overall direction of price

15
00:01:05,330 --> 00:01:06,330
action.

16
00:01:06,330 --> 00:01:11,640
Second, it measure buying pressure relative
to the true range.

17
00:01:11,640 --> 00:01:15,520
This tells us the true magnitude of a gain
or loss.

18
00:01:15,520 --> 00:01:21,060
Third, it creates averages based on the three
timeframes involved (7,14,28).

19
00:01:21,060 --> 00:01:26,220
Fourth, create a weighted average of the three
averages.

20
00:01:26,220 --> 00:01:32,159
By combining three separate time periods,
short-term (usually 7-period), intermediate-term

21
00:01:32,159 --> 00:01:38,360
(usually 14-period), and long-term (usually
28-period), the ultimate oscillator tends

22
00:01:38,360 --> 00:01:40,920
to peak when price peaks.

23
00:01:40,920 --> 00:01:46,189
The intermediate and long-term also include
the short-term time period; thus, the short-term

24
00:01:46,189 --> 00:01:51,830
period is weighted more heavily in the ultimate
oscillator equation.

25
00:01:51,830 --> 00:01:54,890
How to interpret the ultimate oscillator.

26
00:01:54,890 --> 00:02:00,700
Buying pressure and its relationship to the
true range forms the base for the ultimate

27
00:02:00,700 --> 00:02:01,700
oscillator.

28
00:02:01,700 --> 00:02:06,530
Williams believes that the best way to measure
buying pressure is simply subtracting the

29
00:02:06,530 --> 00:02:12,470
close from the low or the prior close, whichever
of the two is the lowest.

30
00:02:12,470 --> 00:02:17,890
This will reflect the true magnitude of the
advance, and hence, buying pressure.

31
00:02:17,890 --> 00:02:23,330
The ultimate oscillator rises when buying
pressure is strong and falls when buying pressure

32
00:02:23,330 --> 00:02:25,430
is weak.

33
00:02:25,430 --> 00:02:30,380
The ultimate oscillator measures momentum
for three distinct timeframes.

34
00:02:30,380 --> 00:02:35,520
The second timeframe is double compared to
the first, and the third timeframe is double

35
00:02:35,520 --> 00:02:37,610
compared to the second.

36
00:02:37,610 --> 00:02:41,990
Even though the shortest timeframe carries
the most weight, the longest timeframe is

37
00:02:41,990 --> 00:02:46,510
not ignored, which should reduce the number
of false divergences.

38
00:02:46,510 --> 00:02:51,920
This is important because the basic buy signal
is based on a bullish divergence and the basic

39
00:02:51,920 --> 00:02:55,620
sell signal is based on a bearish divergence.

40
00:02:55,620 --> 00:03:01,330
By using the weighted average of three different
timeframes the indicator has less volatility

41
00:03:01,330 --> 00:03:06,750
and fewer trade signals compared to other
oscillators that rely on a single timeframe.

42
00:03:06,750 --> 00:03:12,840
Also, I prefer this indicator because the
ultimately oscillator generates fewer divergence

43
00:03:12,840 --> 00:03:18,640
signals than other oscillators due to its
multi-timeframe construction, so the market

44
00:03:18,640 --> 00:03:22,190
noise is greatly reduced.

45
00:03:22,190 --> 00:03:28,080
The ultimate oscillator is a range-bound indicator
with a value that fluctuates between 0 and

46
00:03:28,080 --> 00:03:29,340
100.

47
00:03:29,340 --> 00:03:35,000
Similar to the relative strength index (RSI),
levels below 30 are deemed to be oversold,

48
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:39,610
and levels above 70 are deemed to be overbought.

49
00:03:39,610 --> 00:03:45,000
Trading signals are generated when the price
moves in the opposite direction as the indicator,

50
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:48,160
and are based on a three-step method.

51
00:03:48,160 --> 00:03:53,670
With many momentum oscillators correlating
too heavily to near-term price movements,

52
00:03:53,670 --> 00:03:58,620
Williams developed the ultimate oscillator
to incorporate multiple timeframes to smooth

53
00:03:58,620 --> 00:04:04,021
out the indicator's movements and provide
a more reliable indicator of momentum, with

54
00:04:04,021 --> 00:04:06,980
fewer false divergences.

55
00:04:06,980 --> 00:04:12,350
False divergences are common in oscillators
that only use one timeframe, because when

56
00:04:12,350 --> 00:04:15,620
the price increases the oscillator increases.

57
00:04:15,620 --> 00:04:21,580
Even if the price continues to rise the oscillator
tends to fall forming a divergence even though

58
00:04:21,580 --> 00:04:25,040
the price may still be trending strongly.

59
00:04:25,040 --> 00:04:32,060
Now, how to trade with the ultimate oscillator
In order for the indicator to generate a buy

60
00:04:32,060 --> 00:04:35,940
signal, Williams recommended a three-step
approach.

61
00:04:35,940 --> 00:04:40,180
First, a bullish divergence must form.

62
00:04:40,180 --> 00:04:45,240
This is when the price makes a lower low but
the indicator is at a higher low.

63
00:04:45,240 --> 00:04:52,390
Second, the first low in the divergence (the
lower one) must have been below 30.

64
00:04:52,390 --> 00:04:58,100
This means the divergence started from oversold
territory and is more likely to result in

65
00:04:58,100 --> 00:05:00,410
an upside price reversal.

66
00:05:00,410 --> 00:05:06,460
Third, the ultimate oscillator must rise above
the divergence high.

67
00:05:06,460 --> 00:05:12,400
The divergence high is the high point between
the two lows of the divergence.

68
00:05:12,400 --> 00:05:17,090
Williams created the same three-step method
for sell signals.

69
00:05:17,090 --> 00:05:20,700
First, a bearish divergence must form.

70
00:05:20,700 --> 00:05:25,980
This is when the price makes a higher high
but the indicator is at a lower high.

71
00:05:25,980 --> 00:05:32,600
Second, the first high in the divergence (the
higher one) must be above 70.

72
00:05:32,600 --> 00:05:38,150
This means the divergence started from overbought
territory and is more likely to result in

73
00:05:38,150 --> 00:05:40,750
a downside price reversal.

74
00:05:40,750 --> 00:05:45,890
Third, the ultimate oscillator must drop below
the divergence low.

75
00:05:45,890 --> 00:05:50,410
The divergence low is the low point between
the two highs of the divergence.

76
00:05:50,410 --> 00:05:56,870
In this example, we have classic buy signal,
which met all conditions.

77
00:05:56,870 --> 00:06:03,250
First, we have the bullish divergence forming
between the indicator and security price.

78
00:06:03,250 --> 00:06:09,560
This means the ultimate oscillator formed
a higher low as price recorded a lower low.

79
00:06:09,560 --> 00:06:14,100
The higher low in the oscillator shows less
downside momentum.

80
00:06:14,100 --> 00:06:18,930
Second, the low of the bullish divergence
was below 30.

81
00:06:18,930 --> 00:06:24,240
This is to ensure that prices are somewhat
oversold or at a relative extremity.

82
00:06:24,240 --> 00:06:29,120
Third, the oscillator rose above the high
of the bullish divergence.

83
00:06:29,120 --> 00:06:35,761
Now, technical analysis, requires a little
flexibility and in some cases I don’t like

84
00:06:35,761 --> 00:06:41,389
to wait that much for the oscillator to increase
above the high of the bullish divergence.

85
00:06:41,389 --> 00:06:45,340
An alternative entry I often use is a move
above 50 level.

86
00:06:45,340 --> 00:06:52,360
The chart shows another bullish divergence
signal.

87
00:06:52,360 --> 00:06:57,850
The ultimate oscillator moved to oversold
levels (below 30) as the price fell quite

88
00:06:57,850 --> 00:06:58,850
aggressively.

89
00:06:58,850 --> 00:07:04,480
While the price moved to new lows in, the
indicator held above its prior low and above

90
00:07:04,480 --> 00:07:05,780
30.

91
00:07:05,780 --> 00:07:11,410
The breakout above this high confirmed the
bullish divergence signal.

92
00:07:11,410 --> 00:07:16,360
Also notice that that we have other breakouts
above resistance at a later date.

93
00:07:16,360 --> 00:07:21,920
Even those who missed the initial signal got
a second chance as the price pulled back and

94
00:07:21,920 --> 00:07:23,840
again broke resistance.

95
00:07:23,840 --> 00:07:26,530
Let’s analyze a sell signal.

96
00:07:26,530 --> 00:07:31,840
First, a bearish divergence forms between
the indicator and price.

97
00:07:31,840 --> 00:07:37,290
This means the ultimate oscillator forms a
lower high as price posted a higher high.

98
00:07:37,290 --> 00:07:41,860
The lower high in the oscillator shows less
upside momentum.

99
00:07:41,860 --> 00:07:46,490
Second, the high of the bearish divergence
is above 70.

100
00:07:46,490 --> 00:07:51,870
This is to ensure that prices are somewhat
overbought or at a relative extremity.

101
00:07:51,870 --> 00:07:58,780
Third, the oscillator falls below the low
of the bearish divergence to confirm a reversal.

102
00:07:58,780 --> 00:08:03,720
As in the case of a buy signal, if you want
an earlier entry, pull the trigger when the

103
00:08:03,720 --> 00:08:07,260
ultimate oscillators moves below its 50 level.

104
00:08:07,260 --> 00:08:09,639
And here’s another example.

105
00:08:09,639 --> 00:08:15,090
The stock surged to a new high, but the ultimate
oscillator failed to confirm this high and

106
00:08:15,090 --> 00:08:17,010
formed a lower high.

107
00:08:17,010 --> 00:08:22,220
Also, notice that the indicator became overbought
here.

108
00:08:22,220 --> 00:08:27,430
The breakout below the divergence low confirmed
the bearish signal, and the price declined

109
00:08:27,430 --> 00:08:28,970
sharply afterwards.

110
00:08:28,970 --> 00:08:36,270
Now, I mentioned before that i prefer to skip
the third step, the final confirmation, meaning

111
00:08:36,270 --> 00:08:42,700
the breakout of the divergence high or low,
and use the oscillator’s 50 level as entry.

112
00:08:42,700 --> 00:08:45,330
This approach isn’t always the right decision.

113
00:08:45,330 --> 00:08:49,910
The example shows an unconfirmed bearish signal.

114
00:08:49,910 --> 00:08:56,821
First, the ultimate oscillator became overbought
as the stock moved to new highs, the indicator

115
00:08:56,821 --> 00:08:59,140
posted lower highs.

116
00:08:59,140 --> 00:09:05,800
We have a bearish divergence but the indicator
never broke its divergence low for confirmation.

117
00:09:05,800 --> 00:09:11,290
An entry based on the 50 level would have
brought a loss, because the price reversed

118
00:09:11,290 --> 00:09:12,290
and continued its uptrend.

119
00:09:12,290 --> 00:09:17,140
So, it’s up to you to decide which entry
you prefer.

120
00:09:17,140 --> 00:09:21,990
If you want to be conservative, wait for the
divergence high or low to be broken.

121
00:09:21,990 --> 00:09:27,070
If you want a more aggressive entry, use the
50 level crossover.

122
00:09:27,070 --> 00:09:31,110
Here are some important observations regarding
timeframes.

123
00:09:31,110 --> 00:09:37,040
The ultimate oscillator can be used on intraday,
daily, weekly or even monthly charts.

124
00:09:37,040 --> 00:09:44,100
It is sometimes necessary to adjust its settings
to generate overbought or oversold readings,

125
00:09:44,100 --> 00:09:47,120
which are part of the buy and sell signals.

126
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:53,070
Some stocks or securities may not generate
overbought or oversold readings with the default

127
00:09:53,070 --> 00:09:56,300
settings (7,14,28).

128
00:09:56,300 --> 00:10:00,610
You need to increase sensitivity with shorter
timeframes.

129
00:10:00,610 --> 00:10:05,690
If you plot the oscillator and there are no
overbought or oversold readings, you could

130
00:10:05,690 --> 00:10:12,020
try shortening the timeframe to (4,8,16) to
increase sensitivity.

131
00:10:12,020 --> 00:10:16,170
The opposite is true for securities and stocks
with high volatility.

132
00:10:16,170 --> 00:10:22,089
It is sometimes necessary to lengthen the
timeframes to reduce sensitivity and the number

133
00:10:22,089 --> 00:10:24,300
of signals.

134
00:10:24,300 --> 00:10:28,930
The ultimate oscillator, like all indicators,
has its own limitations.

135
00:10:28,930 --> 00:10:33,430
While the multiple timeframe trading method
for the indicator may help eliminate some

136
00:10:33,430 --> 00:10:37,830
poor trades, it also eliminates many good
ones.

137
00:10:37,830 --> 00:10:42,510
Second you must take into account the fact
that a divergence is not present at all price

138
00:10:42,510 --> 00:10:43,990
reversal points.

139
00:10:43,990 --> 00:10:47,230
The market can reverse without any divergence.

140
00:10:47,230 --> 00:10:53,430
Also, a reversal won't always occur from overbought
or oversold territory.

141
00:10:53,430 --> 00:10:58,360
Maybe the most important note is that waiting
for the oscillator to move above the divergence

142
00:10:58,360 --> 00:11:05,470
high (bullish divergence) or below the divergence
low (bearish divergence) could mean poor entry

143
00:11:05,470 --> 00:11:10,740
point as the price may have already run significantly
in the reversal direction.

144
00:11:10,740 --> 00:11:16,330
That’s why I told you I try to skip this
step, and enter earlier in my trades.

145
00:11:16,330 --> 00:11:22,560
So, as with all indicators, the ultimate oscillator
shouldn't be used in isolation, but rather

146
00:11:22,560 --> 00:11:25,100
as part of a complete trading plan.

147
00:11:25,100 --> 00:11:30,680
And such a plan must include other forms of
analysis such as price action, other technical

148
00:11:30,680 --> 00:11:34,560
indicators, and even fundamental analysis.

149
00:11:34,560 --> 00:11:38,800
If you found value and learned something new,
leave us a like to show your support and make

150
00:11:38,800 --> 00:11:44,520
sure you subscribe and click the bell icon
to stay notified when we release new videos.

151
00:11:44,520 --> 00:11:45,009
Until next time.

